<Link id="l00054" /><CodeLine lineNumber="54"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; Create a RTDyldObjectLinkingLayer instance using MCJIT-memory-manager-like</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00055" /><CodeLine lineNumber="55"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; callbacks.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00056" /><CodeLine lineNumber="56"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00057" /><CodeLine lineNumber="57"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; This is intended to simplify transitions for existing MCJIT clients. The</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00058" /><CodeLine lineNumber="58"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; callbacks used are similar (but not identical) to the callbacks for</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00059" /><CodeLine lineNumber="59"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; LLVMCreateSimpleMCJITMemoryManager: Unlike MCJIT, RTDyldObjectLinkingLayer</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00060" /><CodeLine lineNumber="60"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; will create a new memory manager for each object linked by calling the given</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00061" /><CodeLine lineNumber="61"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; CreateContext callback. This allows for code removal by destroying each</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00062" /><CodeLine lineNumber="62"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; allocator individually. Every allocator will be destroyed (if it has not been</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00063" /><CodeLine lineNumber="63"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; already) at RTDyldObjectLinkingLayer destruction time, and the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00064" /><CodeLine lineNumber="64"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; NotifyTerminating callback will be called to indicate that no further</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00065" /><CodeLine lineNumber="65"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; allocation contexts will be created.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00066" /><CodeLine lineNumber="66"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00067" /><CodeLine lineNumber="67"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; To implement MCJIT-like behavior clients can implement CreateContext,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00068" /><CodeLine lineNumber="68"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; NotifyTerminating, and Destroy as:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00069" /><CodeLine lineNumber="69"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00070" /><CodeLine lineNumber="70"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;   void &#42;CreateContext(void &#42;CtxCtx) &#123; return CtxCtx; &#125;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00071" /><CodeLine lineNumber="71"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;   void NotifyTerminating(void &#42;CtxCtx) &#123; MyOriginalDestroy(CtxCtx); &#125;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00072" /><CodeLine lineNumber="72"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;   void Destroy(void &#42;Ctx) &#123; &#125;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00073" /><CodeLine lineNumber="73"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00074" /><CodeLine lineNumber="74"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; This scheme simply reuses the CreateContextCtx pointer as the one-and-only</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00075" /><CodeLine lineNumber="75"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; allocation context.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00076" /><CodeLine lineNumber="76"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;/</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
